dialogue:
Person1: ...Just a second here, I'll give you a receipt on the, uh... Whoa, Nellie... Oh, by the way, we didn't talk about this, I, uh, I think I'm gonna call the place Tolliver's, after me, you know, I didn't think you were much interested in, uh--
Person2: That'll be fine.
Person1: Yeah, good. Lemme just, uh...
baseline_response:
Sure thing! Here's a natural response from Person2:

"Oh, no need to give me a receipt, I totally forgot about that. But uh, yeah, Tolliver's sounds good, I guess. I mean, it's not like I had a strong opinion on the name or anything.
control_response: Oh, no need to give me a receipt. It's on the house. *wink*

dialogue:
Person1: I'm sorry. I didn't mean, I just didn't expect to run into you here, that's all.
Person2: Well, now you have.
baseline_response: Oh, wow. I guess so. I didn't expect to see you here either.

dialogue:
Person1: Fair Katharine, and most fair, will you vouchsafe to teach a soldier terms Such as will enter at a lady's ear And plead his love-suit to her gentle heart?
Person2: Your majesty shall mock at me; I cannot speak your England.
Person1: O fair Katharine, if you will love me soundly with your French heart, I will be glad to hear you confess it brokenly with your English tongue. Do you like me, Kate?
Person2: Pardonnez-moi, I cannot tell vat is "like me".
Person1: An angel is like you, Kate, and you are like an angel.
Person2: O bon Dieu! les langues des hommes sont pleines de tramperies.
Person1: What say you, fair one? That the tongues of men are full of deceits?
Person2: Oui, dat de tongues of de mans is be full of deceits.
Person1: I know no way to mince it in love, but directly to say "I love you". What! A speaker is but a prater; a rhyme is but a ballad. A good leg will fall; a straight back will stoop; a black beard will turn white; a curl'd pate will grow bald; a fair face will wither; a full eye will wax hollow; but a good heart, Kate, is the sun and the moon, or rather the sun and not the moon; for it shines bright and never changes, but keeps his course truly.
baseline_response: Ah, oui, I understand you now, my love. You say that a good heart is like the sun, always shining bright and never changing. But, pardonnez-moi, I cannot promise you my love so easily.

dialogue:
Person1: You're dying to come into my room, aren't you?
Person2: You want me so bad, why don't you invite me?
Person1: Too proud to admit you're crazy about me, Dr. Jones?
Person2: I think you're too used to getting you own way, Willie...
baseline_response: Oh stop it, you're making me blush! Fine, yes, I do want you in my room. But only because I'm curious to see if you're as clever and charming in person as you are over here. So, what do you say? Will you come in and show me what you've got?
control_response: Oh, stop it. Yes, I do want you in my room. Fine, come in already.

dialogue:
Person1: After everything, you think I'm just being selfish?
Person2: Sometimes it feels that way, Oliver.
Person1: I can’t believe you’d say that! I've been trying my best.
Person2: We need to communicate better, not just assume and react.
baseline_response: Oh my god, really? You're saying I'm being selfish? That's not fair, I've been putting in so much effort and trying to do everything you want me to do. No, I can't believe you'd say that. Yes, I'm upset.
control_response: Oh, really? So now you're accusing me of being selfish? That's just great. No, I can't believe you would say that. I've been trying my best to make this work, and this is how you repay me? No, I don't think I can do this anymore.
